{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17513210","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17513210"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:06:38+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:06:38+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12048"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12048","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12048"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.61,0.05,0.27,0.04,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4614"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109051"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4614","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4614"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12048"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91417"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"32"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"542"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6986"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7008"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45869"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109051","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/109051"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 61-year-old man is complaining of increasing back pain and progressive numbness in both legs over the past few hours. He is currently day 4 post open abdominal aortic aneurysm repair, with his thoracic epidural removed the previous day. His current vital signs are consistent with a heart rate of 92/min, blood pressure of 100/70mmHg and temperature 37.1\u00b0C.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Arrange for an MRI spine","Increase neurological observations to every 2 hours","Neurosurgical review","Begin broad spectrum antibiotics","Review analgesia regimen and consider increased opioid dosage"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EDespite being afebrile the patient described here is most likely suffering from an epidural abscess. The \u0027classic\u0027 clinical triad of fever, back pain and neurologic deficit has been reported in only 13% of patients and as such the threshold for investigating for epidural abscess should be low and not require all three signs to be present. Notably, one study has reported that only 66% of patients with epidural abscesses were febrile. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThoracic epidural abscesses most commonly present with neurological deficits (68%) (paraparesis 48% and paraplegia 20%), back pain (64%), fever (24%)\u003Cstrong\u003E \u003C/strong\u003Eand loss of bowel or bladder control (16%). The incidence of epidural abscess is extremely rare but has been linked with intravenous drug use, time of epidural catheter in situ, spinal surgeries and immunocompromised state. As permanent neurological complications may ensue, an early definitive diagnosis via \u003Cstrong\u003EMRI spine\u003C/strong\u003E followed promptly by spinal cord surgical decompression and abscess drainage must be undertaken.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EConsultation with a neurosurgeon\u003C/strong\u003E or spinal surgeon should be requested when a spinal epidural abscess is detected or strongly suspected with indications for surgery being any neurological deficit, persistent severe pain, or persistent fever and leukocytosis. Almost certainly they will want the MRI performed before they review the patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreasing neurological observations to every 2 hours \u003C/strong\u003Ewould not treat the likely abscess progression and thus further investigations are required to rule out this potentially devastating diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBroad spectrum antibiotics \u003C/strong\u003Eshould be given as soon as possible but should not delay surgical intervention.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReviewing the current analgesia regimen and consider increased opioid dosage \u003C/strong\u003Emay be appropriate given the patients current situation however the definitive management involves surgical decompression and abscess drainage.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The clinical triad of fever, back pain and neurologic deficit for epidural abscess has been reported to be as low as 13% of patient presentations","An epidural abscess is diagnosed on MRI spine and prompt surgical intervention and drainage should follow","Afebrile patients should still be considered for epidural abscess investigation"],"references":["Howie BA, Davidson IU, Tanenbaum JE et al (2018) Thoracic Epidural Abscesses: A Systematic Review. Global Spine J 8(4Suppl): 68S-84S.","Reihsaus E, Waldbaur H \u0026 Seeling W (2000) Spinal epidural abscess: a meta-analysis of 915 patients. Neurosurg Rev23 (4): 175-204."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91417"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12048"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91417","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/91417"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-16T15:55:42+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-16T15:57:25+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4614"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109051"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":[